[2] Fusarium wilt - Georgia
Date: Fri 4 Jun 2010
Source: Southeast Farm Press [edited]
<http://southeastfarmpress.com/vegetables-tobacco/fusarium-wilt-georgia-waermelons-0604/>


Fusarium wilt hits Georgia watermelons
--------------------------------------
Georgia [watermelon] farmers now grow seedless varieties. The switch has
them fighting a deadly plant disease that likes seedless melons as much as
consumers do, says David Langston, University of Georgia. Fusarium wilt
[FW] is now popping up frequently in Georgia watermelon fields.

"It will infect the roots and basically kills the plant," he says. Damage
so far this year [2010] has been localized, but as much as half of some
fields has been lost to it. "We've seen a considerable increase in FW this
year so far, twice as much as previous years," Langston says. Every
watermelon-growing county in Georgia has had reports of FW in seedless melons.

The industry has developed varieties with FW resistance, but all of them
have seeds. Seedless watermelons have become the most widely grown type in
Georgia and other states like Florida and Texas, where farmers are also
seeing increased problems with FW. It can build up in fields that are
planted with watermelons each year, killing even more plants the following
year.

Most important is finding resistant varieties. "Seedless melons have no
resistance at all and [private breeders] have a very difficult time
breeding FW resistance into them," Langston says. FW is just another
disease back on farmers' radars. But it will need to be defeated soon, or
many farmers could be planting themselves into an unavoidable corner in the
coming years.

[byline: Brad Haire]

